{
  "text": "Vitamin K, which is best known for function of blood coagulation, may also play a role in bone metabolism and bonerelated disease. [CITATION_1] Lots of epidemiologic studies have reported that lower vitamin K levels may lead to an adverse outcome on BMD and increase fracture risk. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] Booth et al [CITATION_4] performed a crosssectional study and found that low plasma vitamin K level was associated with low BMD at the femoral neck in men, and with low BMD at the spine in women without using estrogen replacements. Another case-control study conducted by Torbergsen et al [CITATION_5] showed that low plasma vitamin K level was associated with risk of hip fracture. The adjusted odds ratio for per ng/mL increase in plasma vitamin K level was 0.07 [95% confidence interval (95% CI): 0.02-0.32]. Huang et al [CITATION_6] performed a meta-analysis for vitamin K2 supplement, and found that vitamin K2 supplement may improve the vertebral BMD.",
